    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Omnia pri&ugrave;s verbis. qu&agrave;m Armis experiri, sapientem decet. Cineas, Pyrrhi pra[e]cursor.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Cineas"/>
                    <person name="Pyrrhus of Epirus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>It becomes a wise man to try everything by words before resorting to arms. Cineas, Pyrrhus' precursor.</translation> <!--JG: Slight adaptation of Terence's saying (verbis is added)-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="chalengyng hym to fyght">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Monomachia.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Duel.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="I wyll take the victor to taske">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Congrediar</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>cu[m] victore.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>I will join in battle with the conqueror.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Naumachia.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Mock sea battle.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="battayle by see">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Nauale pra[e]liu[m].</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Naval battle.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Animus acer, et pra[e]sens; et acutus idem, atq[ue] versutus, Inuictos viros efficit, Arte coniuncta.
                    Cc. 2. de Oratore. Quasi animum Ca[e]saris, de industria vellet depingere; Romanorum facil&egrave; acerrimi, versutissimi, et Inuictissimi.
                   Compendiaria methodus Excellentia[e].</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Cicero"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/> <!--JG: Not entirely sure-->
                    <book title="De Oratore"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"[It is] a bold and ready mind, acute and quick at expedients, that renders men invincible, and certainly not less effectively if art be united with it." [Watson, 1896] 
                Cicero, book 2 of 'the Orator'. As if he wished to depict the mind of Caesar regarding diligence; easily the most sharp, cunning, and invincible of the Romans.
            A short method of excellence.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="a wretched person,">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>A person of contemptible stature,</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
